			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I have a level 19 enchanter (soon to be Illusionist) in EQ2, but I'm a little disappointed with the class. Some of the things I loved about being an EQ1 chanter (level 65), was that I could change shape into all manor of things and go practically everywere. Oh, sometimes I was a hair's breadth from insta-death while doing so in the more dangerous places, but it was darn fun. From the practical side, being a chanter meant crowd control and reducing the group's down time, which made chanters useful if not outright necessary.
<br />

<br />
However, I avoided reading spoilers on EQ2 and I started a character that would become an enchanter in EQ2 because (since the game design is derivative and, after all, the high level class' name is "illusionist"), I figured it would also turn out to be fun for probably similar reasons. The more I played the game and the more I found out actual details of how the enchanter plays, the more disappointed I became. The game mechanics in EQ2 seem to be working against the enchanter-type class.
<br />

<br />
First, there are practically no illusions for the Illusionist. Oh there is a turn into an elf or human illusion, but that's it. Illusion does not alter faction in EQ2 and even if it did, faction doesn't control aggro so it wouldn't matter. For strictly "fun" illusions, I've seen better from other classes (bear form, for example) that the Illusionist cannot do.
<br />

<br />
Second, there is very little need to reduce down time since health and power regen quickly between battles (more than fast enough to keep up with the spawns). Well, power regen actually, since any heavy fighting needs a healer present and that solves the health regen issue. In EQ2, there is no struggling with being almost out of mana for long periods of time. As a luxury, keeping the cleric buffed with Breeze can be useful sometimes, but then there is the problem with the mere 3 minute breeze duration -- it makes casting Breeze work, not fun. Essentially, breeze turns into a 3 minute power regen buff cast when the need arrises, but is not really effective to keep characters consantly buffed with it.
<br />

<br />
But what about crowd control? In my limited experience (even deep in stormhold and blackburrow), crowd control is not a major concern. This is due to the game mechanics on how aggro is generated -- there is no proximity assist aggro that was the bane of deep dungeon groups in EQ1. This also means pulling is much easier (the probably comes as an unpeasant revelation to EQ1 players who are used to playing monks, but that is for another day) since the exact number of mobs that the group fights is almost always what was expected. There is almost no guesswork in pulling now that mobs are visually linked when selecting them. I mez on a multiple mob pull just out of habit, but the camp doesn't require crowd control -- groups happily and efficiently camp the spots with or without a chanter present.
<br />

<br />
I was never much for charming mobs in EQ1, but there doesn't appear to be a charming spell for the Illusionist. No skin off my nose there, but thought I'd mention it.
<br />

<br />
Oh well. Sony, at least in EQ1, were very slow to address balance issues. I'm not expecting them to fix the EQ2 enchanter any time soon.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
